For that PMR, I had to create a simple test case, so here it is:

public class Main
{
   public static void main(String[] args)
   {
      try
      {
         final long time = System.currentTimeMillis();
         System.out.println("Start Time: " + new Date(time));

         final SimpleThread[] threads = new SimpleThread[3000];

         for (int i = 0; i < threads.length; i++)
         {
            threads[i] = new SimpleThread(i);
            threads[i].start();
         }

         for (int i = 0; i < threads.length; i++)
         {
            try
            {
               threads[i].join();
            }
            catch (InterruptedException e)
            {
               e.printStackTrace();
               break;
            }
         }

         final long time2 = System.currentTimeMillis();
         System.out.println("End Time: " + new Date(time2));
         System.out.println("Execution Time: " + (time2 - time) + "ms");
      }
      catch (Exception e)
      {
         e.printStackTrace();
      }
   }
}

public class SimpleThread extends Thread
{
   private final int num;

   public SimpleThread(int _num)
   {
      super();
      num = _num;
   }

   public void run()
   {
      try
      {
         //System.currentTimeMillis();
         System.out.println("Thread " + num/* + " at time " + new Date()*/);
      }
      catch (Exception e)
      {
         e.printStackTrace();
      }
   }
}


As part of the Java PMR debugging, we noticed that it only runs slow in Eclipse.  When I run using the command prompt, 1.5 runs faster than 1.4.2.  Here is the additional information that the PMR folks returned:

I have done some further analysis on this PMR.  I can recreate it outside Eclipse - in fact I can make it a whole lot worse outside eclipse.

If I use the Runtime.getRuntime().exec("java ......") to run the test app (this is in effect what Eclipse does, it spawns a new instance of java.exe or javaw.exe) the spawed Process pipes the stdin, stdout and stderr back to the parent process.  In my test harness I do not process subprocess.getoutputstream and the process hangs.  Under Eclipse the subprocess.getOutputStream is processed, but not fast enough.  this accounts for the slow response from the Eclipse application.

I have tested this under Sun Java 5.0 and I get exactly the same behaviour.  If you take a look at the Sun Java 2 platform Standard Ed 5.0 documentation.


http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.5.0/docs/api/

Then navigate to the Process Class documentation you will read:


public abstract class Process

extends Object
The ProcessBuilder.start() and Runtime.exec methods create a native process and return an instance of a subclass of Process that can be used to control the process and obtain information about it. The class Process provides methods for performing input from the process, performing output to the process, waiting for the process to complete, checking the exit status of the process, and destroying (killing) the process. 
The methods that create processes may not work well for special processes on certain native platforms, such as native windowing processes, daemon processes, Win16/DOS processes on Microsoft Windows, or shell scripts. The created subprocess does not have its own terminal or console. All its standard io (i.e. stdin, stdout, stderr) operations will be redirected to the parent process through three streams (getOutputStream(), getInputStream(), getErrorStream()). The parent process uses these streams to feed input to and get output from the subprocess. Because some native platforms only provide limited buffer size for standard input and output streams, failure to promptly write the input stream or read the output stream of the subprocess may cause the subprocess to block, and even deadlock. 
The subprocess is not killed when there are no more references to the Process object, but rather the subprocess continues executing asynchronously. 
There is no requirement that a process represented by a Process object execute asynchronously or concurrently with respect to the Java process that owns the Process object. 

The behaviour observed both in Sun 5.0 and IBM 1.5.0 is described above.  the Eclipse application is not processing the output stream of the subprocess promptly enough, this is the cause of your 
failure.  This also explains why when run from a OS command prompt this behaviour is not observed.
This bug should be raised with Eclipse - not sure how to do this but I guess there is a forum.

Note: from searching for other bugs, it looks like 136655 might be related, but that is with the TFTP and not Eclipse itself, so I'm opening this as a separate bug.  I can't tell if they are really the same problem or not, but it looked like it might be related somehow.

import java.util.StringTokenizer;
public class petitessai {
	public static void main(String[] args) {

		StringTokenizer T = new StringTokenizer("3 1 2");

		afficher(T);


	}

	public static void afficher (StringTokenizer S){
		if (S.hasMoreTokens()){

			ecrire(S);
			String temp =S.nextToken();
			afficher(S);
			ecrire(S);


		}
	}

	public static void ecrire (StringTokenizer K){
		System.out.println(" Suite de nombre :");
		while (K.hasMoreTokens()){
			String t=K.nextToken();
			System.out.print(t);
	}


	}

}

